32 [within 3 business days] as soon as practicable and without delay after obtaining [the
33 consent or] such an order or the denial of [the consent or] a request for such an order, as
34 applicable.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. Chapter 432B of NRS is hereby amended by adding thereto the
2 provisions set forth as sections 2 and 3 of this act.
3 Sec. 2. 1. If an agency which provides child welfare services is required
4 to provide consent before a child who is in the custody of the agency may receive
5 non-emergency medical [or mental health treatment,] care that is recommended
6 by a provider of health care, the agency which provides child welfare services
7 shall provide or deny such consent not later than 14 days after [such consent is
8 requested.] the caseworker assigned to the child receives written notice of the
9 recommendation or referral for such care.
10 2. If any person or entity, including, without limitation, a person legally
11 responsible for the psychiatric care of a child appointed pursuant to NRS
12 432B.4685, is required to provide consent before a child who is in the custody of
13 an agency which provides child welfare services may receive medical or mental
14 health treatment, the agency which provides child welfare services shall:
15 (a) Make reasonable efforts to obtain such consent not later than 14 days
16 after the [agency which provides child welfare services becomes aware]
17 caseworker assigned to the child receives written notice of the need for the
18 treatment, which may be demonstrated by, without limitation, a referral for the
19 treatment; and
20 (b) Notify the person or entity with whom the child is placed [within 3
21 business days] as soon as practicable and without delay after obtaining such
22 consent or the denial of such consent.
23 3. If an order of the court is required before a child who is in the custody of
24 an agency which provides child welfare services may receive non-emergency
25 medical [or mental health treatment,] care that is recommended by a provider of
26 health care, the agency which provides child welfare services shall:
27 (a) Make reasonable efforts to initiate such an order not later than 14 days
28 after the [agency which provides child welfare services becomes aware]
29 caseworker assigned to the child receives written notice of the [need for the
30 treatment;] recommendation or referral for such care; and
31 (b) Notify the person or entity with whom the child is placed [within 3
32 business days] as soon as practicable and without delay after obtaining such an
33 order or the denial of a request for such an order.
34 4. Nothing in this section shall be construed to prohibit a party with proper
35 standing from seeking a court order for the medical treatment of a child in the
36 custody of a child welfare agency.
37 5. As used in this section, “provider of health care” has the meaning
38 ascribed to it in NRS 629.031.
